{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637241"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:40:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:40:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17642"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17642"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10356"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75466"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10356"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17642"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60976"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"7744"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24218"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24222"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75466"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA research team wants to study the prevalence of vitamin D deficiency among primary school children in rural Australia. They decide to randomly select 20 schools from a list of 200 rural schools and test all children at the selected schools.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this sampling method?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stratified random sampling","Simple random sampling","Systematic sampling","Convenience sampling","Cluster sampling"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecluster sampling\u003C/strong\u003E, where natural groups (schools) are randomly selected and then all units (students) within those clusters are sampled. This method is particularly useful when it would be impractical to randomly sample individual students across all 200 schools.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple random sampling\u003C/strong\u003E would involve randomly selecting individual students from the entire population of rural school children\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStratified random sampling\u003C/strong\u003E would involve dividing the population into subgroups based on specific characteristics and then sampling from each stratum\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystematic sampling\u003C/strong\u003E would involve selecting every nth student from an ordered list\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConvenience sampling\u003C/strong\u003E would involve selecting the most easily accessible students without random selection\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile cluster sampling is more practical and cost-effective in this scenario, it may be less precise than simple random sampling because students within the same school may share similar characteristics (e.g. socioeconomic status, sun exposure) that affect vitamin D levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cluster sampling involves randomly selecting groups (clusters) and then sampling all units within those clusters.","Cluster sampling is useful when individual sampling is impractical or when natural groupings exist in the population.","Cluster sampling is less precise than simple random sampling due to potential similarities within clusters."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60976"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17642"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60976"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T20:45:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T00:55:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10356"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75466"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:30","updatedAt":"20